ly regarded to have been an important driving force behind secularization of schools in Norway, not least because the total number of weekly lessons in religious education gradually was reduced. This book problematizes this thesis and enlightens how important politicians and policymakers within the Labour Party defended religious education. A central point is that this defense must be seen within the frames of a liberally oriented protestant theology. Thus, the study highlights the diversity of ideas in Norwegian politics in the post-war period and demonstrates how important impulses in Norwegian politics can be viewed against a wider international background.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aBildung. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aNorwegen. 4aSekularisierung. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCultural history.  aNorway.  aeducation.  asecularization.0 cEPUBz97831112063700 cprintz978311120474140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111206097zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111206097zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111206097/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA